## Pre-Release Cheat-sheet
(Cheat-sheet for LimeStone

Section 1 - general blocks

1, VRBrea (French number);
VRBrea means variable area followed by a French number for which VRBrea it is, then ended in a semicolon, it is the beginning of a VRBrea.
2, VRBrea nd:
This is the end of a VRBrea, nd means end then followed by a colon.
3, _comt"'your comment here'"
This is a comment, its _comt then a double quote then single quote, your text in the middle, then a single quote then double quote.
4, vrb crte
This is the start of a variable creation and its easy to understand, vrb means variable, crte means create.
5,"your string here"
This is a general string, you need this for multiple things like naming a variable or naming a function action, though when using a string it starts with a double quote and ends with a single quote.
6, say; 'your text here'
This is a print command,  its say; then a space and then a single quote, your text, then another single quote.
7, DF"function action name'
This is declaring a function, DF means Do Function then a double quote, then the name of a previously defined function action, then a single quote.
8, N
This means do thing one and thing two at the same time.
9, Nd
This means do thing one then thing two.
10, vlu=(value)
This is assigning a value you to something, currently only used at the end of creating a variable, vlu means value, then an equal sign, then a number (which is the value).
11, dF
This means does Function, only used currently for defining the logic of a function action.
12, WI
This is the beginning of a condition line, it means What If but its basically just if in any other coding language.
13, Lwsd WI |
This is the start of a conditional loop, under it must be a condition, Lwsd means always, WI means what if (block 12 on the cheat sheet) then ended with a space then a |.

Section 2 - arithmetic blocks

1, +,-,*,/
These are the basic arithmetic symbols, + is addition, - is subtraction, * is multiplication, / is division.
2, on
This means onto, which is used for global addition besides inside a VRBrea.
3, in
This means into and is used for local addition(inside a VRBrea only) and global multiplication.
4, of
This means off of and is used for global subtraction and division.
5, set
This means set... and it does what it says, it sets the value of a chosen variable to the value you want it to be.

Section 3 - basic common lines of code in LimeStone

1, vrb crte "variable name" vlu=(value)
This is creating a variable, vrb crte is first (see block 4 in Section 1) then a general string of what teh name is (see block 5 section 1) then vlu=(value) (see block 10 section 1).
2, DF crte "function action name" dF'+,-,*,/ (name of variable or value) in, of (name of target variable)' |
This is defining a function action we first have DF crte (see first half of block 7 section 1 and second half of block 4 section 1) then a string for the name then dF'+,-,*,/ (variable or value) of,in (target variable)' (see block 11 section 1, then block 1 section 2, then block 3 and 4 section 2) then ends with a |.
3, WI (what you want the condition to be, for example:)variable>100
This is a condition, first we got WI (see block 12 section 1) then what then what the condition is which is usuall a variable, then <, >, or =, then target value.

Cheat-sheet will be updated along side grammar sheet and news (every three days)
